@Bouncey yeah! that would be ok :+1: and my suggested instruction update
> The function `destroyer` will be called with an array (*first argument*), followed by one or more values (*rest arguments*).
Remove the values from the given array which are equal to the values passed in rest of the arguments.

These are some of the solutions. Probably, for ES5 solution, also recommending the use of `Array#slice`, `Function#call`. And `Array#includes` and `spread operator` too for ES6.

using ES6
```js
function destroyer(arr, ...args) {
  return arr.filter((el) => !args.includes(el))
}
```
or using ES5
```js
function destroyer(arr) {  
  // grab the other args
  var args = [].slice.call(arguments, 1);

  // filter the given array
  return arr.filter(function (el) {
    // return elements not in the args
    return args.indexOf(el) === -1;
  });
}
```

